 s = \"111000\"\nOutput: 2\nExplanation: Use the first operation two times to make s = \"100011\".\nThen, use the second operation on the third and sixth elements to make s = \"101010\".\n\nExample 2:\n\nInput: s = \"010\"\nOutput: 0\nExplanation: The string is already alternating.\n\nExample 3:\n\nInput: s = \"1110\"\nOutput: 1\nExplanation: Use the second operation on the second element to make s = \"1010\".\n\n \nConstraints:\n\n1 <= s.length <= 105\ns[i] is either '0' or '1'.\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def minFlips(self, s: str) -> int:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nclass Solution:\n    def minFlips(self, s: str) -> int:\n        n = len(s)\n        # Create two reference strings of alternating patterns\n        alt1 = '01' * (n // 2 + 1)\n        alt2 = '10' * (n // 2 + 1)\n        \n        # Initial count of flips needed for the first window\n        flips1 = sum(s[i] != alt1[i] for i in range(n))\n        flips2 = sum(s[i] != alt2[i] for i in range(n))\n        \n        min_flips = min(flips1, flips2)\n        \n        # Use sliding window technique to check all possible rotations\n        for i in range(n):\n            # Remove the effect of the character that is sliding out of the window\n            if s[i] != alt1[i]:\n                flips1 -= 1\n            if s[i] != alt2[i]:\n                flips2 -= 1\n            \n            # Add the effect of the new character that is sliding into the window\n            if s[i] != alt1[i + n % 2]:\n                flips1 += 1\n            if s[i] != alt2[i + n % 2]:\n                flips2 += 1\n            \n            # Update the minimum flips needed\n            min_flips = min(min_flips, flips1, flips2)\n        \n        return min_flips\n```\n\nThis solution uses a sliding window approach to efficiently calculate the minimum number of type-2 operations required to make the string alternating. It first calculates the number of flips needed for the initial string configuration against two possible alternating patterns. Then, it slides the window across the string, updating the flip counts and keeping track of the minimum flips required.", "estimated_date": 1622937600000}